SIMPLE: onyx
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Onyx
<hw>O"nyx</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/ a claw,
finger nail, a veined gem. See <er>Nail</er>, and cf.
<er>Onycha</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Chalcedony in
parallel layers of different shades of color. It is used for making
cameos, the figure being cut in one layer with the next as a
ground.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Same as <cref>Mexican onyx</cref>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A deep jet-black color.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Onyx marble</b></col>, <col><b>Mexican
onyx</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a banded variety of marble or calcium
carbonate resembling onyx. It is obtained from Mexico in various colors
ranging from white to deep black.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>onyx</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: onyx
<hw>o"nyx</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Deep,
jet-black.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oo</ent>⟦br⟧
